How do gcc optimisations work under the hood? <p>This problem arose while I was writing a program to retrieve file sizes. I wanted to learn more about file management and other file related things, so I wrote a c++ program using the fstream and filesystem libraries to retrieve a bunch of information about all the files in a user specified folder (retrieved using <code>cin</code>) and its subfolders, then organise the data based on one of the information types returned from the file (file size in my case). The program is not an optimised one, far from it, but it's fast enough to return a few thousand files in a couple of seconds. The logic is for this process is relatively simple. Clear a 'dump.txt' file, then get the folder using <code>cin</code>, and adds it to a vector containing the directories to search through. Then iterate over the directories in the vector using a while loop, and store all the file info in a custom struct <code>fileInfo</code>, and append it to a <code>vector&lt;fileInfo&gt;</code>. Now that we have all the file data in a vector, iterate through it and put it all in 'dump.txt'. The source code is below.</p>
<pre><code>#include &lt;iostream&gt;
#include &lt;map&gt;
#include &lt;vector&gt;
#include &lt;cmath&gt;
#include &lt;filesystem&gt;
#include &lt;fstream&gt;
using namespace std;
using namespace filesystem;

struct fileInfo {
    public:
        path name;
        path dir;
        size_t size;
        fileInfo(path _filename, path _fileDir, size_t _fileSize) {
            name = _filename;
            dir = _fileDir;
            size = _fileSize;
        }
};

enum NDS {name, dir, size};
const map&lt;const unsigned short, const string&gt; byteSuffixes = {
    {0, &quot;bytes&quot;},
    {1, &quot;KB&quot;},
    {2, &quot;MB&quot;},
    {3, &quot;GB&quot;},
    {4, &quot;TB&quot;}
};

void vectorSort(vector&lt;fileInfo&gt; &amp;_v, const NDS _sortby) {
    vector&lt;fileInfo&gt; res;
    map&lt;size_t, fileInfo, greater&lt;size_t&gt;&gt; fileSizes;
    map&lt;path, fileInfo&gt; fileNames;
    map&lt;path, fileInfo&gt; fileDirectories;
    for (const fileInfo _f : _v) {
        fileSizes.insert({_f.size, _f});
        fileNames.insert({_f.name, _f});
        fileDirectories.insert({_f.dir, _f});
    }

    switch (_sortby) {
        case NDS::name: {
            for (const auto name : fileNames) {res.push_back(name.second);}
            break;
        }
        case NDS::dir: {
            for (const auto directory : fileDirectories) {res.push_back(directory.second);}
            break;
        }    
        case NDS::size: {
            for (const auto size : fileSizes) {res.push_back(size.second);}
            break;
        }
        default:
            break;
    }

    _v = res;
}

void clearFile(const string filename) {
    fstream dump(filename);
    if (dump.is_open()) {
        dump.ignore(2);
    } else {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Failed&quot;;
    }
    dump.close();

    ofstream clear_file(filename);
    if (clear_file.is_open()) {
        clear_file.close();
    }
}

int main() {
    string initDir;
    cout &lt;&lt; &quot;Folder to search through: &quot;;
    cin &gt;&gt; initDir;
    if (!filesystem::exists(path(initDir))) {
        cout &lt;&lt; &quot;File not found&quot;;
        return -1;
    }
    vector&lt;path&gt; directories = {path(initDir)};

    vector&lt;fileInfo&gt; fileMap;
    size_t i = 0;
    size_t longestFileName = 0;
    size_t longestDirName = 0;

    clearFile(&quot;dump.txt&quot;);
    fstream dump(&quot;dump.txt&quot;);

    if (!dump.is_open()) {
        cerr &lt;&lt; &quot;\n ERROR OPENING DUMP \n&quot;;
        return -1;
    }

    while (i &lt; directories.size()) {
        try {
            const path p = directories[i];
            directory_iterator dirIter = directory_iterator(p);
            for (const path dir : dirIter) {
                if (is_directory(dir)) {
                    directories.push_back(dir);
                } else {
                    size_t fileSize = file_size(dir);
                    if (fileSize &lt; 1000000) {continue;}
                    path filename = dir.filename();
                    path parentDir = dir.parent_path();
                    fileMap.push_back(fileInfo(filename, parentDir, fileSize));
                    longestFileName = (filename.string().length() &gt; longestFileName) ? filename.string().length() : longestFileName;
                    longestDirName = (parentDir.string().length() &gt; longestDirName) ? parentDir.string().length() : longestDirName;
                }
            }
        } catch (const filesystem_error&amp; e) {
            cerr &lt;&lt; e.what() &lt;&lt; '\n';
        }
        i++;
    }

    const size_t column1spacing = longestFileName + 4;
    const size_t column2spacing = longestDirName + 4;

    dump &lt;&lt; &quot;FILE NAME&quot;;
    for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column1spacing-9; _++) {dump &lt;&lt; ' ';}
    dump &lt;&lt; &quot;|   FILE LOCATION&quot;;
    for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column2spacing-16; _++) {dump &lt;&lt; ' ';}
    dump &lt;&lt; &quot;|   FILE SIZE (bytes)\n&quot;;
    for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column1spacing; _++) {dump &lt;&lt; '-';}
    dump &lt;&lt; '|';
    for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column2spacing; _++) {dump &lt;&lt; '-';}
    dump &lt;&lt; &quot;|--------------------\n&quot;;

    vectorSort(fileMap, NDS::size);

    for (const auto x : fileMap) {
        const string filename = x.name.string();
        const string fileDir = x.dir.string();

        const unsigned short power1000 = static_cast&lt;unsigned short&gt;(floor(log10(x.size)/3));

        const size_t fileSize = static_cast&lt;size_t&gt;(floor(x.size/(pow(1000, power1000))));

        dump &lt;&lt; filename;
        for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column1spacing-filename.length(); _++) {dump &lt;&lt; ' ';}
        dump &lt;&lt; &quot;|   &quot; &lt;&lt; fileDir;
        for (size_t _ = 0; _ &lt; column2spacing-fileDir.length()-3; _++) {dump &lt;&lt; ' ';}
        dump &lt;&lt; &quot;|   &quot; &lt;&lt; fileSize &lt;&lt; &quot; &quot; &lt;&lt; byteSuffixes.at(power1000) &lt;&lt; &quot;\n&quot;;
    }

    dump.close();
    cout &lt;&lt; &quot;File scan successful, type \&quot;exit\&quot; to exit.\n&quot;;
    string buff;
    cin &gt;&gt; buff;

    return 0;
}
</code></pre>
<p>The one problem I have, however, happens when running the program against one particular directory. When I run the program with the initial directory <code>C:\Users\verdo\Documents\randomStuff</code>, which is the directory in which the executable I'm running sits, the program runs indefinitely. Or, more accurately, until I force kill vscode from task manager, or until vscode just crashes. At the end, if you leave vscode to its devices, the text file where the file info is normally dumped is about 5 gigabytes, which is concerning given <code>randomStuff</code> contains a total of 5 files, inclusing the dump itself, which is normally completely empty. This is interesting given that the program handles directories like <code>C:\Users</code> just fine, despite having a number of files far in excess of <code>randomStuff</code>, and <code>C:\Users</code> contains <code>randomStuff</code>. My first step was to look through my code and double check everything, mainly the safeguard implementations. Everything was working fine there, so it had nothing to do with empty or missing directories, or any other problem which might cause the file info fetch to fail. And I couldn't identify any other places in the code in which this sort of file size explosion would occur. My next step was to look into the dump file to try and see of there were any clues there. Opening a 5GB text file is unreasonable in any text editor, so I reran the program and the immediately closed vscode from task manager. The resulting text file was now only 30 MB, which is still ludicrous, but enough to open vscode and view the dump. It consisted of one line, starting with FILE NAME, then followed by 26 million spaces. Interesting, but it wasn't overly helpful in identifying the root cause. My next step was to run it through gdb, surely a debugger can identify the problem, right? I add the breakpoint, start gdb, run it through in its entirety, and it works exactly as expected, the dump has 3 lines all less than 80 characters long. I remove the breakpoint and rerun the program again from gdb. Works fine. Evidently this must imply that gcc and gdb are executing the program fundamentaly different ways, and after reading some of the gdb logs, it occured to me that gdb doesn't use the same flags that I use when compiling with gcc. So I remove some of the flags from gcc, and the moment the <code>-Og</code> flag is removed, the program runs fine. I find this interesting, given that (as far as I understand) <code>-Og</code> enables optimisations. My question is this: How do gcc optimisations work under the hood, whats the main difference between the different optimisation flags, and what would <code>-Og</code> be doing to trigger this obscure bug? Also, is there any way to determine when this bug might happen so that you don't have to deal with this bug?</p>

